        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1883-11-19T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1883-11-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="264" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d264">
                <head>No. 264.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Frelinghuysen</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Lowell</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1883-11-19">
                            <hi rend="italic">November</hi> 19,
                            1883</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 705.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Mr. Hoppin’s several dispatches and telegrams
                        in relation to the citizenship of Patrick O’Donnell have been received. In
                        his dispatch No. 647 Mr. Hoppin requests to be instructed whether under all
                        the circumstances thus far reported the question of O’Donnell’s American
                        citizenship is to be considered as settled in his favor.</p>
                <pb facs="0546" n="476" xml:id="pg_476"/>
                <p>I have now to instruct you that, upon the facts before the Department,
                        Patrick O’Donnell’s naturalization appears to be established, and in the
                        absence of proof to the contrary he is to be regarded as a citizen of the
                        United States.</p>
                <p>The Department has been requested to seek a complimentary and courteous
                        relaxation of such bar or other rules in England as might deny to counsel
                        from the United States the right to plead in O’Donnell’s defense during the
                        approaching trial. I have informed the applicants that the system of law
                        which prevails in this country, as in Great Britain, is jealous of any
                        interference by the executive with the judiciary departments, but should
                        there be any necessity for the English court to be assured of the high
                        position of counsel who go from this country to take part in the defense of
                        O’Donnell, you will give such assurance. This being done, they, or those
                        associated with them, can submit to the court such proposition as they deem
                        the interest of their client demands.</p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>FRED’K T. FRELINGHUYSEN.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
